        <p>The mental load of single parenthood is real and it's heavy. You're managing your own grief, anger, or exhaustion while trying to be steady for your kids. Counseling is one of the most effective tools for carrying that — not because it makes things easier, but because it gives you somewhere to process what's happening so it doesn't come out sideways.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>Check your EAP first.</strong> If you're employed, there's a good chance your employer offers an Employee Assistance Program with free counseling sessions — typically 3–8 sessions at no cost to you, completely confidential. Most people don't know it exists. Look for "EAP" in your HR benefits portal or call HR and ask.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>How do you know if you need it?</h2>
        <p>Dads are good at minimizing their own struggles — there's always a kid who needs something more urgently. But the signs that you'd benefit from talking to someone are worth taking as seriously as you'd take them in your child. A few that tend to get waved off:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>The anger is showing up sideways</strong> — snapping at the kids over small things, road rage, a short fuse that wasn't there before.</li>
          <li><strong>You're not sleeping,</strong> or you're sleeping to escape. Either direction is a signal.</li>
          <li><strong>You're running on autopilot</strong> — going through the motions of the day but not really present for any of it.</li>
          <li><strong>You're leaning harder on a drink, a screen, or anything else to take the edge off</strong> at the end of the day.</li>
          <li><strong>The intrusive thoughts about the divorce, the ex, or the custody situation won't quiet down,</strong> replaying on a loop.</li>
          <li><strong>You can't remember the last time you felt like yourself.</strong></li>
        </ul>
        <p>None of these mean something is wrong with you. They mean you're carrying a heavy load without enough support — which is exactly what counseling is for. You don't have to be in crisis to deserve help.</p>

        <h2>Types of counseling worth knowing about</h2>

        <h3>Individual therapy</h3>
        <p>One-on-one sessions with a therapist focused on you — your stress, your coping, your patterns. This is the right starting point for most people. A good individual therapist helps you process what's happening and build better responses to it.</p>

        <h3>Co-parenting counseling</h3>
        <p>Specifically designed for separated parents who need to communicate and parent together. Different from couples counseling — the goal isn't the relationship, it's the kids. This can be enormously useful when communication with your co-parent is a constant source of stress. Sometimes called "parent coordination."</p>

        <h3>Family therapy</h3>
        <p>Involves you and your children together. Useful when your kids are struggling with the transition and you want a professional to help facilitate those conversations in a structured way. Not right for every situation — talk to a therapist first about whether it fits yours.</p>

        <h3>Crisis counseling</h3>
        <p>Short-term, focused intervention for acute situations. If you're in a mental health crisis right now, see the <a href="{{ '/mental/helplines/' | url }}">Helplines page</a> — that's the fastest path to help.</p>

        <h2>How to find a good therapist</h2>
        <p>The relationship matters more than any credential. A good fit — someone you can be honest with and who seems to actually understand your situation — is more important than someone with an impressive CV.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Psychology Today's therapist finder</strong> (<a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/therapists" target="_blank" rel="noopener">psychologytoday.com/us/therapists</a>) — the most comprehensive directory. Filter by issue (divorce, family, stress), insurance, and sliding scale. Read bios — some therapists specialize in men's issues or fatherhood.</li>
          <li><strong>Open Path Collective</strong> (<a href="https://openpathcollective.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">openpathcollective.org</a>) — network of therapists offering reduced-rate sessions ($30–80) to people without adequate mental health coverage.</li>
          <li><strong>SAMHSA treatment locator</strong> (<a href="https://findtreatment.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">findtreatment.gov</a>) — for finding community mental health centers near you.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Questions worth asking a potential therapist</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Have you worked with single parents or fathers going through custody situations?</li>
          <li>What's your approach to therapy? (Look for something practical, not just talk-and-reflect.)</li>
          <li>Do you offer a sliding scale or reduced rates?</li>
          <li>What's your cancellation policy? (Important when you have kids and scheduling is unpredictable.)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>How to afford it</h2>

        <h3>Free options</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Employee Assistance Program (EAP)</strong> — see the callout above. Start here.</li>
          <li><strong>Community mental health centers</strong> — federally funded clinics that charge on a sliding scale based on income. Many charge little or nothing for low-income clients. Search "[your county] community mental health center."</li>
          <li><strong>University training clinics</strong> — supervised graduate students offer therapy at significantly reduced rates. Quality is generally good — they're closely supervised and often highly motivated.</li>
          <li><strong>Open Path Collective</strong> — reduced-rate sessions ($30–80), as mentioned above.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Insurance</h3>
        <p>Mental health parity laws require most insurance plans to cover mental health at the same level as physical health. Check what your plan covers — many cover a set number of therapy sessions per year after your copay. Call the number on the back of your insurance card and ask specifically about outpatient mental health benefits.</p>

        <h3>Online therapy</h3>
        <p>Platforms like BetterHelp and Talkspace connect you with licensed therapists via text, video, or phone. Convenient if scheduling in-person sessions is hard. They're paid services (typically $60–100/week) but often cheaper than traditional therapy, and some offer financial aid. Not a replacement for in-person care in a crisis, but useful for ongoing support.</p>

        <h2>On being a dad who asks for help</h2>
        <p>A lot of men were raised to handle it alone — to be the one who fixes problems, not the one who has them. If part of you balks at the idea of therapy, that's not a character flaw, it's conditioning. But it's worth being honest about where that instinct leads: bottled-up stress doesn't disappear, it leaks out — onto your kids, your health, your relationships.</p>
        <p>Reframe it the way you'd want your son or daughter to see it. Getting help when the load is heavy isn't weakness — it's the same kind of strength you'd be proud of in them. You'd want your kid to talk to someone if they were struggling. The same applies to you. And there's a direct payoff: a dad who's processing his own stuff is a steadier, more present parent. Taking care of yourself isn't separate from taking care of your kids — it's part of it.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>It usually takes a few tries to find the right therapist.</strong> If the first one doesn't click after 2–3 sessions, try another. It's not a failure — it's just how it works. The right match is worth finding.</p>
        </div>

        <p>If what you need first is peer connection rather than professional help, the <a href="{{ '/mental/support-groups/' | url }}">Support Groups guide</a> covers communities built for exactly your situation. And if you're in a hard moment right now, the <a href="{{ '/mental/helplines/' | url }}">Helplines page</a> has immediate resources.</p>

        <p><em>This page is general information. If you're experiencing a mental health crisis, contact the 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline by calling or texting 988.</em></p>
